It is because field injection only happen after the test class is instantiated . So you would find `TestUtil` is not injected yet when the test class &#39;s constructor is executing.

You can use the constructor injection to solve it : 

``` java
public class UserQuestionCommentRestControllerTest extends IntegrationTestContext {

     @Autowired
     public UserQuestionCommentRestControllerTest(TestUtil testUtil) throws Exception {
       super(testUtil);
       token = testUtil.getToken(testUsername, testPassword);
     }

}

public class IntegrationTestContext {

    public IntegrationTestContext(TestUtil testUtil){
       this.testUtil = testUtil;
    }
}

```

Or a more natural way for testing is keep using the field injection but use `@BeforeEach` to configure the token : 

``` java
public class UserQuestionCommentRestControllerTest extends IntegrationTestContext {

    private String token;
   

   //no more constructor 

   @BeforeEach
   void beforeEach(){
      this.token = testUtil.getToken(testUsername, testPassword); 
   }
}


```

